{"type":"message","id":"b5c77150","parentId":"b44f2063","timestamp":"2026-04-15T02:05:24.480Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me analyze the sessions. I need to exclude this cron session (e7885813-0446-4101-a171-941c2416848e) and identify only ACTIVE master-orchestrator sessions.\n\nActive sessions (status=running, not ended):\n1. `agent:master-orchestrator:cron:6f3323ef-607e-42a0-b946-611913081d31` — \"Cron: 5p Progress Report - DTLX\" — started 1776199558073 = let me calculate: 1776199558073ms / 1000 = 1776199558s → let me think about this. 1776218668479 - 1776199558073 = wait, these are in ms. 1776218668479 - 1776199558073 = 19110406ms... That seems wrong. Actually these are Unix timestamps in milliseconds.\n\n\nLet me recalculate: 1776218668479 - 1776199558073 = 19110406ms ≈ 5h 18m 30s. That means the cron started around 1776199558073, which is approximately 1776199558 in Unix seconds. So the session started 5 hours and 18 minutes ago. Looking at the second session more carefully—it appears to have ended based on the endedAt timestamp of 1776214477348, but it's still showing as running in the sessions list, which seems contradictory. Let me trace through the actual data to understand what's happening with these session states.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the sessions API only returns up to 20 results regardless of the activeMinutes filter I specified, so the second cron session I was looking for might not even be in this batch. The three cron sessions I'm seeing are all currently active, and there's also the Lead Telegram session that's running.\n\nBut I'm noticing the Lead Telegram session has both a status of \"running\" and an endedAt timestamp of 1776212660602, which is before the current updatedAt time of 1776218158344—that's a contradiction. Similarly, the cron session labeled \"Cron: 5p Progress Report\" shows \"running\" status but has an endedAt time that's earlier than its updatedAt, which doesn't make sense either. These are clearly lingering session entries that should have been marked as ended.\n\nLet me recalculate the runtime for the cron:6f3323ef session—it's been about 5 hours and 18 minutes since it started. I'm working through the exact millisecond conversions to get the precise duration.\n\nNow I'm checking the status of another cron session that appears to be still running with no end timestamp recorded yet. For the cron session with id `ed2d0b5d-fc56-42eb-a8fc-973a48024df7`, the start time is 1776214290785 and the runtime is only 10,277ms (about 10 seconds), which suggests it completed quickly. The cron session with id `ac986a8d-2425-40c7-835b-ed9b101b0bff` started even earlier at 1776156271891 and is still running after about 17 hours, but the session messages show what looks like an interrupted attempt to send something to a Telegram group.\n\nLooking at the cron sessions currently active, I see three main ones: one monitoring 5p Progress reports for DTLX that's been running for about 5 hours, another doing the same for QLHV with minimal runtime, and a third that's been running for roughly 17 hours. There's also the cron session I just spawned that's currently active.\n\nThe main sessions like `agent:master-orchestrator:main` and `agent:master-orchestrator:telegram:direct:6053576134` are both marked as done, and the group Telegram sessions appear to have ended as well. The orphaned cron sessions are still hanging around but aren't really active anymore. I'm focusing on the agent sessions now since that's what the cron was asking about.\n\nFor the running sessions, I'm calculating how long they've been active: `cron:6f3323ef` has been running for about 5 hours and 18 minutes since around 8:44 PM, while `cron:e7885813` is just starting up at just after 2:04 AM. The third cron session `cron:ed2d0b5d` is still active but with minimal runtime.\n\nNow I'm identifying the key sessions to report on: the three cron sessions are all actively running, with the DTLX 5p monitor having the longest uptime at over 5 hours, while the QLHV monitor just started and the agent status session is also fresh. I need to calculate the exact durations for each.\n\nFor the DTLX 5p monitor, the current time is 1776218668479 milliseconds, and it started at 1776199558073, which gives me about 5 hours 18 minutes 31 seconds of runtime.\n\nFor the agent status cron, it started at 1776218668036 and has been running for just 441 milliseconds, so that's less than a second. I need to figure out which session is the cron running in—it's the one that's currently executing with ID `d2b4e2ec-8bb7-4f2e-9400-fc79898dcebf`.\n\nThe three active master-orchestrator cron sessions are: the DTLX 5p monitor running for about 5 hours 18 minutes, the QLHV 5p monitor that's just restarted with minimal runtime, and the agent status cron that's been running for less than a second. I'm formatting the report now to send to Lead via Telegram.\n\nNow I'm calculating the exact runtime for the DTLX monitor more precisely—starting from around 8:44 PM and running through 2:04 AM, which gives me roughly 5 hours and 18 minutes.\n\nGenerating the runtime report... For the QLHV session, it's restarting every 5 minutes based on the heartbeat logic, so the short 10-second runtime makes sense — it completed quickly and is waiting for the next cycle.\n\nNow I'm putting together the full report to send to Lead via Telegram, checking the current time in UTC for the header.","thinkingSignature":"dbfaf4a5d14d1162bb49e10dc7df53f3d7d3da39618e4898f07917fd53438479"},{"type":"text","text":"Now compiling. I can see 3 active master-orchestrator cron sessions (excluding this one) plus one stale cron session. Let me send the report.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_hrxt01mmjjtq_1","name":"sessions_send","arguments":{"sessionKey":"agent:master-orchestrator:telegram:direct:6053576134","agentId":"master-orchestrator","message":"🌐 Orbis — Agent Status | 02:04 UTC 15 Apr\n\nActive sessions: 